{"parse":{"title":"Edgelands","pageid":47802272,"revid":841192513,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">\"Edgeland\" redirects here. For the album by Karl Hyde, see <a href=\"/wiki/Edgeland_(album)\" title=\"Edgeland (album)\">Edgeland (album)</a>.</div>\n<p><b>Edgelands</b> are the transitional, <a href=\"/wiki/Liminality\" title=\"Liminality\">liminal</a> areas of space to be found on the boundaries of country and town - with the spread of <a href=\"/wiki/Urbanisation\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Urbanisation\">urbanisation</a>, an increasingly important facet of the twenty-first century world.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Further_reading\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Further reading</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Edgelands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The concept of Edgelands was introduced by <a href=\"/wiki/Marion_Shoard\" title=\"Marion Shoard\">Marion Shoard</a> in 2002, to cover the disorganised but often fertile hinterland between planned town and over-managed country.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  However a century and a half earlier, <a href=\"/wiki/Victor_Hugo\" title=\"Victor Hugo\">Victor Hugo</a> had already highlighted the existence of what he called \"bastard countryside...ugly but bizarre, made up of two different natures, which surrounds certain great cities\";<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> while <a href=\"/wiki/Richard_Jeffries\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Richard Jeffries\">Richard Jeffries</a> similarly explored the London edgeland in <i>Nature near London</i> (1883).\n<a href=\"/wiki/Alice_Coleman\" title=\"Alice Coleman\">Alice Coleman</a> (Kings College London, dept geography) in 2nd Land Use Survey of Great Britain, refers to  \"rurban fringe\". Indicating a similar landscape but with negative overtones.\n</p><p>Nevertheless it was only in the last decades of the twentieth century - as a distinct realm of Nature increasingly disappeared beneath the commodifying impact of globalising <a href=\"/wiki/Late_capitalism\" title=\"Late capitalism\">late capitalism</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> - that the significance of the unstructured borderlands between organised town and organised country, part man-made, part natural,<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> both for wildlife and for human exploration, came into fuller focus. <a href=\"/wiki/Psychogeography\" title=\"Psychogeography\">Psychogeography</a> charted the London orbital, while bombsites, canal banks and brownfield sites were documented in poetry and prose, film and photography;<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> and the borderlands as an untapped, transgressive resource became almost the object of a new cult.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Edgelands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"div-col columns column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 22em; -webkit-column-width: 22em; column-width: 22em;\">\n<ul><li><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Deep_topography&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Deep topography (page does not exist)\">Deep topography</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Geocriticism\" title=\"Geocriticism\">Geocriticism</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Human_geography\" title=\"Human geography\">Human geography</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Edward_Soja#Thirdspace\" title=\"Edward Soja\">Thirdspace</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Topophilia\" title=\"Topophilia\">Topophilia</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/W._G._Sebald\" title=\"W. G. Sebald\">W. G. Sebald</a></li></ul></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Edgelands&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Andrew Walker - 2002 Aspects of Lincoln: Discovering Local History - Page 134 1473836131 \"AN 'EDGE-LAND': THE DEVELOPMENT OF THE WITHAM VALLEY EAST OF CANWICK ROAD by Dennis Mills THE TERM 'EDGE-LAND' has been coined recently for the concept of a neglected area on the fringe of a city. Frequently such ...\"</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/our-beautiful-edgelands-a-dark-light-on-the-edge-of-town-2217071.html\">Our beautiful edgelands</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Quoted in <a href=\"/wiki/Robert_Macfarlane_(writer)\" title=\"Robert Macfarlane (writer)\">Robert Macfarlane</a>, <i>Landmarks</i> (2015) p. 231</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"/wiki/Frederic_Jameson\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Frederic Jameson\">Frederic Jameson</a>, <i>The Jameson Reader</i> (2002) p. 251</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">M. Pratt, <i>My Wild Northumbria</i> (2015) p. 176 and 208</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Robert Macfarlane, <i>Landmarks</i> (2015) p. 232</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">T. Fry, <i>Design in the Borderlands</i> (2014) p. 159</span>\n</li>\n</ol></di